# 42_palettes_scriptable_smoke — seventh row-bound model Scriptable
# (s243 m2), closing the s243 arc. Modelled on
# 29_swatches_scriptable_smoke — palettes are the SwatchLibrary's
# other pool (parallel to swatches; same two-tier defaults+custom
# storage, same string-id identity, same project-scoped lifetime).
#
# Two addressing surfaces, one router:
#
#   palettes         — collection. ONE registry entry. Set verbs (new,
#                      delete, duplicate, rename, activate,
#                      find_by_name) and set queries (count, all_ids,
#                      custom_ids, default_ids, active_id).
#   palettes.<iid>   — per-instance proxy. NOT in the registry —
#                      materialised on demand, destroyed at end-of-
#                      statement. Element verbs (rename, activate) and
#                      element queries (name, is_default, is_active,
#                      swatch_count, swatches, iid).
#
# The shared `palettes` prefix is load-bearing: the router splits a
# dotted token on the first `.`, looks the prefix up in the registry,
# and asks the matched object to resolve the suffix. Collection name
# and proxy prefix MUST be the same string.
#
# ── Test isolation ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every palette this script creates is bound to a script-local variable
# at creation time. Existing palettes (defaults + custom that were in
# the project when the script started) are NEVER touched: not renamed,
# not deleted. The teardown step at the bottom deletes only the
# palettes we created, by bound iid.
#
# Same iid-binding pattern as 29_swatches_scriptable_smoke.
#
# ── Active palette side effects ───────────────────────────────────────────
#
# `palettes new` and `palettes duplicate` BOTH make the new palette
# active (matches the panel's UX contract; AddPaletteCommand's
# set_make_active flag is set true by the Scriptable). This means the
# active palette walks forward across the BUILD UP phase: a → b → c.
# By the time we get to VALIDATE, c is active. Asserts that check
# is_active are written against that walk, not against any
# pre-existing baseline.
#
# Activation is NOT undoable — set_active_palette is transient working
# state, deliberately outside undo. Same posture as the panel's
# dropdown click. Manual Ctrl+Z after the script finishes walks back
# through the four CRUD commands (new a, new b, new c, duplicate a)
# but NOT through the activate calls.
#
# ── Undo coverage ─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
# Every mutating CRUD verb pushes a command into the doc's
# CommandHistory. The smoke can't directly assert "the stack grew by
# one" — there's no script verb for undo today. What the smoke DOES
# verify is the round-trip: rename A then rename back, etc. Manual
# Ctrl+Z after the script is the second half of the test — every
# CRUD operation should be individually undoable.
#
# ── Phases ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
#
#   1. BUILD UP  — capture baseline counts, create three test palettes,
#                  bind each iid to a variable (a / b / c).
#   2. VALIDATE  — exercise collection queries, defaults-tier guards,
#                  proxy verbs, proxy queries, find_by_name on each
#                  bound palette, activate round-trip.
#   3. TEAR DOWN — delete every test palette; verify count returns to
#                  baseline.

#[sub] === Phase 1: BUILD UP ===
#[sub] Capture baseline so teardown can verify cleanup. count is an
#[sub] integer, comparable in assert via simple equality. The id list
#[sub] queries are useful for visual diff but not directly comparable
#[sub] via `assert == var` (commas in substituted values break the
#[sub] line tokeniser, same constraint as the swatches smoke).

get palettes count
set count_before to result
get palettes all_ids
get palettes custom_ids
get palettes default_ids
get palettes active_id
set active_before to result

#[sub] Create three test palettes. `palettes new` returns the new iid;
#[sub] `set X to result` binds it. Each new palette becomes active as
#[sub] a side effect of AddPaletteCommand's m_make_active flag — the
#[sub] active walk goes a -> b -> c across the three creates.

palettes new "smoke_test_a"
set a to result
assert palettes.a name == "smoke_test_a"
assert palettes.a is_default == false
assert palettes.a is_active == true

palettes new "smoke_test_b"
set b to result
assert palettes.b name == "smoke_test_b"
assert palettes.b is_default == false

palettes new "smoke_test_c"
set c to result
assert palettes.c name == "smoke_test_c"
assert palettes.c is_default == false
# c was just created -> c is active, a and b are not.
assert palettes.c is_active == true
assert palettes.a is_active == false

#[sub] iid query — round-trips the binding key. A script can `get
#[sub] palettes.<var> iid` to verify it has the right handle.

get palettes.a iid
get palettes.b iid
get palettes.c iid

#[sub] === Phase 2: VALIDATE ===

#[sub] Collection-level queries after BUILD UP. count should be
#[sub] baseline + 3. all_ids / custom_ids / default_ids printed for
#[sub] visual diff. default_ids must be identical to baseline (the
#[sub] Scriptable can't touch defaults).

get palettes count
get palettes all_ids
get palettes custom_ids
get palettes default_ids
get palettes active_id

#[sub] find_by_name — collection verb (parameterised-query workaround,
#[sub] same shape as swatches.find_by_name). Invoke-shaped today
#[sub] because query() can't take args. First-hit semantics; our names
#[sub] are unique within the test so each returns the bound iid.

palettes find_by_name "smoke_test_a"
set found_a to result
palettes find_by_name "smoke_test_b"
set found_b to result
palettes find_by_name "smoke_test_c"
set found_c to result
# Miss returns "" — operator can confirm visually below.
palettes find_by_name "no_such_palette_in_any_tier"
assert palettes.found_a name == "smoke_test_a"
assert palettes.found_b name == "smoke_test_b"
assert palettes.found_c name == "smoke_test_c"

#[sub] Proxy rename round-trip on `a`. RenamePaletteCommand carries
#[sub] old + new name. Skip-no-op guard: rename to current name
#[sub] doesn't push a command.

palettes.a rename "smoke_test_a_renamed"
assert palettes.a name == "smoke_test_a_renamed"
palettes.a rename "smoke_test_a"
assert palettes.a name == "smoke_test_a"

#[sub] Collection-level rename round-trip on `b`. Same
#[sub] RenamePaletteCommand, accessed via the collection-with-iid form.

palettes rename b "smoke_test_b_renamed"
assert palettes.b name == "smoke_test_b_renamed"
palettes rename b "smoke_test_b"
assert palettes.b name == "smoke_test_b"

#[sub] Activate round-trip. Activation is NOT undoable, but the
#[sub] round-trip still verifies the verb works on both addressing
#[sub] surfaces: collection-with-iid (`palettes activate b`) and proxy
#[sub] (`palettes.c activate`).

palettes activate b
assert palettes.b is_active == true
assert palettes.c is_active == false
palettes.c activate
assert palettes.c is_active == true
assert palettes.b is_active == false

#[sub] Duplicate `a`. New iid, fresh entry, " copy" appended to name
#[sub] (library-side default when new_name arg is empty). The
#[sub] duplicate becomes active as a side effect of
#[sub] AddPaletteCommand::already_added's m_make_active flag.

palettes duplicate a
set a_dup to result
assert palettes.a_dup name == "smoke_test_a copy"
assert palettes.a_dup is_default == false
assert palettes.a_dup is_active == true

#[sub] Palette contents — swatch_count and swatches queries. A freshly
#[sub] minted custom palette has no swatches; a duplicate of a fresh
#[sub] palette also has no swatches. Per-palette swatch ops are out of
#[sub] scope for s243 m2 (`add_swatch`, `remove_swatch`,
#[sub] `reorder_swatch` are deferred); we only verify the read side.

get palettes.a swatch_count
get palettes.a swatches
get palettes.a_dup swatch_count
get palettes.a_dup swatches

#[sub] Defaults-tier guard. If the project has at least one defaults
#[sub] palette, exercising rename / delete on its iid should silently
#[sub] fail (verb returns Null, no command pushed). Activation IS
#[sub] allowed on defaults (it's a per-project pointer, not a
#[sub] mutation), so this is one place the defaults-guard intentionally
#[sub] differs from the swatches one.
#[sub]
#[sub] No-target case (project shipped with empty defaults) is
#[sub] documented but not asserted — the test passes either way. The
#[sub] guard's correctness is enforced by the Scriptable's
#[sub] defaults-tier check.

get palettes default_ids
# (manual inspection of the result above tells the operator whether
# defaults exist; the smoke continues regardless)

#[sub] === Phase 3: TEAR DOWN ===
#[sub] Delete every test palette. Each delete pushes
#[sub] RemovePaletteCommand which snapshots the palette value AND the
#[sub] active-state pre-remove for full round-trip undo. The currently-
#[sub] active palette is one of ours (c was activated last, then a_dup
#[sub] become active via duplicate), so the active pointer walks back
#[sub] through the deletes — undefined which palette ends up active
#[sub] after the last delete (likely "" until the panel falls back).

palettes delete a
palettes delete b
palettes delete c
palettes delete a_dup

#[sub] Verify cleanup. count should be back to baseline. Visual
#[sub] inspection of the id lists below confirms no residue remains.

get palettes count
assert palettes count == count_before
get palettes custom_ids
get palettes default_ids
get palettes active_id

#[sub] Registry sanity — list at end. `palettes` should appear exactly
#[sub] once, alongside `swatches` / `layers` / `guides` / etc. No
#[sub] `palettes.<iid>` entries despite the many transient proxies
#[sub] materialised across this run (one per dotted addressing line
#[sub] above, every proxy destroyed at end-of-statement).

list

#[sub] s243 m2 smoke complete — collection verbs, proxy verbs, proxy
#[sub] queries, defaults-tier guard, find_by_name, activate
#[sub] round-trip, and duplicate "copy"-naming all exercised. Every
#[sub] CRUD verb pushed a command into history; manual Ctrl+Z after
#[sub] this script finishes should walk the undo stack back through
#[sub] every operation (activation calls excluded; they're not
#[sub] undoable by design).
